<subsubsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-a-rhombus">
    <title>Area of a Rhombus</title>
    <p>
        A <m>\textbf{rhombus}</m> is a quadrilateral with all four sides of <m>\textbf{equal length}</m>.. All its sides are equal and the diagnols bisect at <m>90 ^\circ</m>. Which other quadrilateral has all its sides equal?
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{ Properties of a Rhombus:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    All sides are equal in length. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Opposite angles are equal.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Diagonals bisect each other at right angles. 
                </p>
            </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Diagonals bisect the interior angles.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Some examples of a rhombus are Tiles or patterns in flooring, or The shape of playing cards (diamonds suit).
                    </p>
                </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A rhombus has a diagonal of 10 cm and another diagonal of 24 cm. Find:
            </p>
            <p>
             1. The area of the rhombus.
            </p>
            <p>
               2.The length of one side of the rhombus.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>

    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="rhombus">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Define the rhombus vertices
            \coordinate (A) at (0,3);
            \coordinate (B) at (3,0);
            \coordinate (C) at (0,-3);
            \coordinate (D) at (-3,0);
            % Draw the rhombus with thick pink outline
            \draw[thick, magenta!80] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;

            % Draw diagonals with dashed lines
            \draw[dashed] (A) -- (C);
            \draw[dashed] (B) -- (D);

            % Mark right angles at the intersection of diagonals
            \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
            \draw[thick] (O) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);

            % Label the vertices
            \node[above] at (A) {A};
            \node[right] at (B) {B};
            \node[below] at (C) {C};
            \node[left] at (D) {D};
            \node[below right] at (O) {O};
